pwd - print working directory - tell you the current directory
ls - list - list the contents of the current directory
cd - change directory - to go inside a directory be specifying the directory name
cd\ - takes you to your home directory in terminal
cd / - takes you to the root folder
cd .. - this command take you back one directory, like the back button in windows
cat - open a file right in terminal, only you have to specify the file name (which is case-sensitive), if you are already in the directory go right ahead and type cat and filename but you can also specify the path and filename and open a file right there in terminal without actually navigating to the folder in which the file resides (if a file name has space in it, for eg: 'Linux Commands', then the command would be "cat Linux\ Commands")
whoami - tells you the current logged in username
clear - clears your terminal screen (can also type ctrl + l)
ip address - tells you, your ip address
cp - copy command, cp filename(you want to copy) filename(the destination), if the file doesn't exits, new file will be created
rm - remove command
sudo - gives you administrative access for one command
